  <!-- CARD 1 -->
  <div class="endpoint-card">
    <div class="card-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
      <span class="method-pill pill-get">GET</span>
      <span class="endpoint-path">/getUsers</span>
      <span class="endpoint-desc">List all users</span>
      <span class="chevron">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <div class="issues-list">
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Verb in URL path</strong>
            REST URLs identify <em>resources</em>, not actions. The verb "get" is redundant — the HTTP method GET already expresses the intent. Mixing verbs into paths breaks the uniform interface constraint.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>camelCase naming</strong>
            URL paths should use lowercase letters and hyphens (kebab-case), never camelCase, to avoid ambiguity across case-sensitive servers and improve readability.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Singular vs plural inconsistency risk</strong>
            Collection endpoints must use the plural noun (<code>/users</code>) to clearly represent a collection of resources.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="block-grid">
        <div class="block block-bad">
          <div class="block-label">❌ Original</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-get" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">GET</span> /getUsers</div>
        </div>
        <div class="block block-good">
          <div class="block-label">✅ Corrected</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-get" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">GET</span> /users</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- CARD 2 -->
  <div class="endpoint-card">
    <div class="card-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
      <span class="method-pill pill-post">POST</span>
      <span class="endpoint-path">/user/delete/5</span>
      <span class="endpoint-desc">Delete a user</span>
      <span class="chevron">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <div class="issues-list">
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Wrong HTTP method</strong>
            POST is for creating resources. Deletion must use the DELETE method, which is idempotent — calling it multiple times produces the same result. Using POST for deletion hides intent and prevents caching layers and API gateways from behaving correctly.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Action verb "delete" embedded in path</strong>
            The path should only contain the resource identifier. The action is conveyed by the HTTP method (DELETE), making the word "delete" in the URL entirely redundant and misleading.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Singular resource noun</strong>
            Using <code>/user</code> instead of <code>/users</code> breaks consistency with the collection endpoint and implies only one user exists in the system.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Non-idempotent semantics for a destructive action</strong>
            Deleting with POST means the operation is not idempotent by HTTP contract. Retry logic, proxies, and clients may behave unpredictably.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="block-grid">
        <div class="block block-bad">
          <div class="block-label">❌ Original</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-post" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">POST</span> /user/delete/5</div>
        </div>
        <div class="block block-good">
          <div class="block-label">✅ Corrected</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-delete" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">DELETE</span> /users/5</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- CARD 3 -->
  <div class="endpoint-card">
    <div class="card-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
      <span class="method-pill pill-get">GET</span>
      <span class="endpoint-path">/createUser?name=Jo</span>
      <span class="endpoint-desc">Create a user</span>
      <span class="chevron">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <div class="issues-list">
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Wrong HTTP method — GET must be safe &amp; idempotent</strong>
            GET requests must never cause side effects. Creating a resource is a state-changing operation. Using GET for creation allows the request to be cached, bookmarked, or pre-fetched by browsers, inadvertently triggering unintended resource creation.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Sensitive data in query string</strong>
            User data (name, email, passwords) passed as query parameters appear in server logs, browser history, and HTTP referrer headers — a serious security and privacy risk. POST body data is not logged by default.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Verb "create" in path</strong>
            Same violation as /getUsers — the action is expressed by the HTTP method POST, not the path. The path should only name the resource collection: <code>/users</code>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="block-grid">
        <div class="block block-bad">
          <div class="block-label">❌ Original</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-get" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">GET</span> /createUser?name=Jo</div>
        </div>
        <div class="block block-good">
          <div class="block-label">✅ Corrected</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-post" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">POST</span> /users</div>
          <div style="font-size:.78rem;color:var(--muted);margin-top:.5rem">Body: <code style="color:var(--info)">{"name":"Jo"}</code> &nbsp;·&nbsp; Content-Type: application/json</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- CARD 4 -->
  <div class="endpoint-card">
    <div class="card-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
      <span class="method-pill pill-put">PUT</span>
      <span class="endpoint-path">/updateAllUsers</span>
      <span class="endpoint-desc">Update all users</span>
      <span class="chevron">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <div class="issues-list">
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Verb "update" in path</strong>
            The action is already expressed by PUT. Embedding the verb is redundant and violates the uniform interface principle.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Bulk update on entire collection is dangerous without scoping</strong>
            PUT on a collection replaces the <em>entire</em> collection. This is almost never the intended behaviour. If partial field updates are needed, PATCH is the correct method. For a specific user, the ID must appear in the path.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="issue-item">
          <span class="issue-icon">🚫</span>
          <div class="issue-text">
            <strong>Missing resource identifier</strong>
            REST resources should be individually addressable. <code>/users/{id}</code> targets one user; <code>/users</code> with PUT/PATCH implies a bulk operation that requires careful design and explicit documentation.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="block-grid">
        <div class="block block-bad">
          <div class="block-label">❌ Original</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-put" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">PUT</span> /updateAllUsers</div>
        </div>
        <div class="block block-good">
          <div class="block-label">✅ Corrected (single user — full replace)</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-put" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">PUT</span> /users/{id}</div>
          <div class="block-label" style="margin-top:.8rem">✅ Corrected (single user — partial update)</div>
          <div class="code-line"><span class="method-pill pill-patch" style="font-size:.65rem;padding:.2rem .5rem">PATCH</span> /users/{id}</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── CORRECTED FULL API ── -->
  <div class="section-title">✅ Corrected API — Complete Reference</div>

  <div class="quick-ref">
    <div class="quick-ref-row header-row">
      <div class="qr-cell">Method</div>
      <div class="qr-cell">Endpoint</div>
      <div class="qr-cell">Description</div>
    </div>
    <div class="quick-ref-row">
      <div class="qr-cell"><span class="method-pill pill-get">GET</span></div>
      <div class="qr-cell" style="font-family:monospace">/users</div>
      <div class="qr-cell" style="color:var(--muted)">Retrieve all users (supports <code>?page=</code> &amp; <code>?limit=</code>)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="quick-ref-row">
