  <div id="tab-guide" class="tab-content">

    <div class="section-card open" id="card-guide">
      <div class="section-header" onclick="toggleCard('card-guide')">
        <div class="section-title">
          <div class="section-icon icon-guide">📖</div>
          REST API Best Practices
        </div>
        <div class="section-meta">
          <span class="section-count">8 rules</span>
          <span class="chevron">▼</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="practices-grid">

          <div class="practice-card">
            <div class="practice-icon">🏷️</div>
            <div class="practice-title">Use Nouns, Not Verbs</div>
            <div class="practice-desc">URLs identify resources. HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE) communicate the action. Never put verbs like "get", "create", or "delete" in your URL paths.</div>
            <div class="practice-example">✅ GET /users
❌ GET /getUsers
❌ POST /createUser</div>
          </div>

          <div class="practice-card">
            <div class="practice-icon">📦</div>
            <div class="practice-title">Use Plural Nouns for Collections</div>
            <div class="practice-desc">Resource collections should always be plural. This makes it clear you're accessing a collection and a member of it, and keeps the API consistent.</div>
            <div class="practice-example">✅ GET /users
✅ GET /users/5
❌ GET /user
❌ GET /user/5</div>
          </div>

          <div class="practice-card">
            <div class="practice-icon">🔢</div>
            <div class="practice-title">Version Your API</div>
            <div class="practice-desc">Always include a version in your API path from day one. This allows you to make breaking changes in future versions without disrupting existing clients.</div>
            <div class="practice-example">✅ /v1/users
✅ /v2/users
❌ /users (no version)</div>
          </div>

          <div class="practice-card">
            <div class="practice-icon">🛠️</div>
            <div class="practice-title">Use Correct HTTP Methods</div>
            <div class="practice-desc">Each HTTP method has a specific semantic meaning. Misusing them breaks client expectations, caching, and idempotency guarantees.</div>
            <div class="practice-example">GET    → Read (safe, idempotent)
POST   → Create
PUT    → Full replace (idempotent)
PATCH  → Partial update
DELETE → Remove (idempotent)</div>
          </div>

          <div class="practice-card">
            <div class="practice-icon">🔒</div>
            <div class="practice-title">Never Pass Sensitive Data in URLs</div>
            <div class="practice-desc">Query strings and path parameters appear in server logs, browser history, and referrer headers. Always use the request body for sensitive or complex data.</div>
            <div class="practice-example">✅ POST /users  { body: {...} }
❌ GET /createUser?password=abc
❌ GET /users?token=secret123</div>
          </div>

          <div class="practice-card">
            <div class="practice-icon">📝</div>
            <div class="practice-title">Use Meaningful Status Codes</div>
            <div class="practice-desc">Return the most specific and accurate HTTP status code. Never return 200 OK for errors. Clients rely on status codes to handle responses correctly.</div>
            <div class="practice-example">✅ 201 Created (not 200) for POST
✅ 204 No Content for DELETE
✅ 409 Conflict for duplicates
❌ 200 OK for everything</div>
          </div>

          <div class="practice-card">
            <div class="practice-icon">🔗</div>
            <div class="practice-title">Use Consistent Naming (kebab-case)</div>
            <div class="practice-desc">URLs are case-insensitive but conventionally lowercase. Use hyphens for multi-word resource names. Avoid camelCase, underscores, or mixed conventions.</div>

