<!-- ENDPOINT 2: POST /user/delete/5         -->
<!-- ======================================== -->
<div class="endpoint-card">
    <div class="endpoint-header" onclick="toggle('ep2')">
        <span class="method-badge method-post">POST</span>
        <span class="endpoint-url bad">/user/delete/5</span>
        <span class="endpoint-desc">Delete a specific user</span>
        <span class="tag tag-severity-high">4 Issues</span>
        <span class="chevron" id="chevron-ep2">▼</span>
    </div>

    <div class="arrow-row">
        <span class="old-endpoint">POST /user/delete/5</span>
        <span class="arrow">→</span>
        <span class="new-endpoint">DELETE /users/5</span>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint-body" id="ep2">
        <div class="body-inner">
            <div class="two-col">
                <div class="problem-box">
                    <div class="box-title red">⚠ Problems Identified</div>
                    <ul class="problem-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🔴</span>
                            <span><strong>Wrong HTTP method:</strong> Using <code style="color:#f87171">POST</code> for deletion is a critical REST violation. POST means "create a new resource." Deletion has its own dedicated method: <code style="color:#4ade80">DELETE</code>.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🔴</span>
                            <span><strong>Action verb in URL:</strong> <code style="color:#f87171">/delete</code> is an action, not a resource. The DELETE HTTP method already communicates the intent — putting it in the URL is redundant and anti-REST.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🟡</span>
                            <span><strong>Singular resource name:</strong> <code style="color:#f87171">/user/</code> should be <code style="color:#4ade80">/users/</code>. REST convention uses plural nouns for collections, whether you're operating on one or many.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🟡</span>
                            <span><strong>Not idempotent:</strong> POST is not idempotent. DELETE should be — calling <code style="color:#4ade80">DELETE /users/5</code> twice should return 204 then 404, which is safe and predictable.</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="fix-box">
                    <div class="box-title green">✅ Fixes Applied</div>
                    <ul class="problem-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Changed method to <strong>DELETE</strong> — the semantically correct HTTP verb for resource removal.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Removed <code>/delete</code> from the URL. The endpoint is now <code style="color:#4ade80">DELETE /users/5</code> — clean and self-describing.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Pluralized to <code style="color:#4ade80">/users</code> for consistency with the collection endpoint.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Returns <code>204 No Content</code> on success — standard for DELETE with no response body needed.</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tab-row">
                <button class="tab-btn active" onclick="switchTab('ep2', 'request')">Request</button>
                <button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab('ep2', 'response')">Response</button>
