                    <div class="box-title red">⚠ Problems Identified</div>
                    <ul class="problem-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🔴</span>
                            <span><strong>GET used for state mutation:</strong> This is the most dangerous violation. GET must be safe and side-effect free. Using it to create data means browsers, CDNs, and caches can inadvertently trigger user creation by prefetching or caching the URL.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🔴</span>
                            <span><strong>Sensitive data in query string:</strong> User data like <code style="color:#f87171">?name=Jo</code> (and potentially email/password) in the URL gets logged in server logs, browser history, and proxy logs — a serious security vulnerability.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🔴</span>
                            <span><strong>Verb in URL:</strong> <code style="color:#f87171">/createUser</code> is an action. The HTTP method POST already communicates "create." The URL should be <code style="color:#4ade80">/users</code>.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🟡</span>
                            <span><strong>Incomplete data model:</strong> A user needs more than just a name. Data belongs in a structured JSON request body, not fragmented query parameters.</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="fix-box">
                    <div class="box-title green">✅ Fixes Applied</div>
                    <ul class="problem-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Changed to <strong>POST</strong> — the correct method for creating a new resource. POST is not idempotent, which correctly models "creating a new user."</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>All user data moved to the <strong>JSON request body</strong> — secure, structured, and not logged by default.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>URL simplified to <code style="color:#4ade80">POST /users</code> — posting to the collection creates a new member of that collection.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Returns <code>201 Created</code> with a <code>Location</code> header pointing to the new resource.</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
