    </div>

    <div class="endpoint-body" id="ep4">
        <div class="body-inner">
            <div class="two-col">
                <div class="problem-box">
                    <div class="box-title red">⚠ Problems Identified</div>
                    <ul class="problem-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🔴</span>
                            <span><strong>Wrong HTTP method for partial updates:</strong> <code style="color:#f87171">PUT</code> means "replace the entire resource." If you omit a field, it gets nulled. For partial updates, use <code style="color:#4ade80">PATCH</code> which only modifies specified fields.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🔴</span>
                            <span><strong>Verb in URL:</strong> <code style="color:#f87171">/updateAllUsers</code> is an action phrase. The HTTP method already expresses the update intent. The URL should describe the resource being updated.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🔴</span>
                            <span><strong>Dangerous mass operation:</strong> Bulk updating all users with no targeting criteria or safeguards is a catastrophic design. It needs explicit scoping, confirmation mechanisms, and proper authorization checks.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">🟡</span>
                            <span><strong>No resource identifier:</strong> There's no way to know which user(s) are being updated. A proper endpoint either targets <code style="color:#4ade80">/users/{id}</code> for single updates or uses a well-defined bulk endpoint.</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="fix-box">
                    <div class="box-title green">✅ Fixes Applied</div>
                    <ul class="problem-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Single user: <code style="color:#4ade80">PATCH /users/{id}</code> — partial update of one user. Only provided fields are changed.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Full replacement: <code style="color:#4ade80">PUT /users/{id}</code> — replaces the entire user resource (all fields required).</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Bulk updates: <code style="color:#4ade80">PATCH /users/bulk</code> with explicit ID targeting in the request body — never "all users" without explicit selection.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="icon">✓</span>
                            <span>Returns <code>200 OK</code> with updated resource, or <code>204 No Content</code> if no body is returned.</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
