        @media (max-width: 768px) {
            header h1 { font-size: 1.5rem; }
            .score-banner { flex-direction: column; }
            .corrected-table { font-size: 0.78rem; }
            .corrected-table th, .corrected-table td { padding: 0.5rem 0.6rem; }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
    <h1>🔍 REST API Audit Report</h1>
    <p>Complete violation analysis with corrections and REST principle explanations</p>
</header>

<div style="max-width:1100px;margin:2rem auto;padding:0 1rem;">

    <!-- Score Banner -->
    <div class="score-banner">
        <div class="score-circle">F</div>
        <div class="score-text">
            <h2>API Design Quality Score</h2>
            <p>4 endpoints audited — every single one has violations</p>
            <div class="progress-bar-wrap" style="width:200px;">
                <div class="progress-bar" style="width:8%;"></div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="stats">
            <div class="stat-item">
                <span class="stat-number red">12</span>
                <span class="stat-label">Total Violations</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-item">
                <span class="stat-number red">6</span>
                <span class="stat-label">Critical</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-item">
                <span class="stat-number orange">4</span>
                <span class="stat-label">Major</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-item">
                <span class="stat-number" style="color:#ecc94b;">2</span>
                <span class="stat-label">Minor</span>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Global REST Principles -->
    <div class="global-principles">
        <h2>📚 Core REST Principles Being Violated</h2>
        <div class="principles-grid">
            <div class="principle-card">
                <div class="icon">🏷️</div>
                <h3>Nouns, Not Verbs</h3>
                <p>URLs identify resources (nouns). HTTP methods express the action (verbs). Never put verbs like <em>get</em>, <em>create</em>, <em>delete</em> in a URL path.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="principle-card">
                <div class="icon">🔧</div>
                <h3>Correct HTTP Methods</h3>
                <p>GET=read, POST=create, PUT/PATCH=update, DELETE=delete. Using the wrong method breaks caching, idempotency, and client expectations.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="principle-card">
                <div class="icon">📂</div>
                <h3>Resource Hierarchy</h3>
                <p>Use plural nouns and hierarchical paths: <code>/users</code>, <code>/users/5</code>. Actions on a specific resource go via its identifier, not inline in the path.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="principle-card">
                <div class="icon">🔒</div>
                <h3>Safe &amp; Idempotent Methods</h3>
                <p>GET must be safe (no side effects). PUT must be idempotent. POST is neither. Misuse breaks HTTP contracts relied on by browsers, caches, and proxies.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="principle-card">
                <div class="icon">📦</div>
                <h3>Request Body vs Query String</h3>
                <p>Query strings are for filtering/searching existing resources. Resource creation data must go in the request body, never in the URL.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="principle-card">
                <div class="icon">🎯</div>
                <h3>Consistent Naming</h3>
                <p>Use lowercase, hyphen-separated, plural nouns consistently. Mixed conventions (<code>getUsers</code> vs <code>user</code> vs <code>updateAllUsers</code>) break predictability.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Filter Bar -->
    <div class="filter-bar">
        <span class="filter-label">Filter:</span>
        <button class="filter-btn active" id="btn-all" onclick="filterCards('all')">All (4)</button>
        <button class="filter-btn" id="btn-critical" onclick="filterCards('critical')">🔴 Critical</button>
        <button class="filter-btn" id="btn-major" onclick="filterCards('major')">🟠 Major</button>
        <button class="filter-btn" id="btn-minor" onclick="filterCards('minor')">🟡 Minor</button>
        <button class="expand-all-btn" id="expand-all-btn" onclick="toggleAll()">Expand All</button>
    </div>

    <!-- Endpoint Cards -->
    <div class="main-content" style="padding:0;max-width:100%;">

        <!-- Card 1: GET /getUsers -->
        <div class="endpoint-card" data-severities="critical,minor" id="card-0">
            <div class="endpoint-header" onclick="toggleCard(0)">
                <span class="method-badge method-get">GET</span>
                <span class="endpoint-path broken">/getUsers</span>
                <span class="issue-count-badge">3 issues</span>
                <span class="chevron" id="chevron-0">▼</span>
            </div>
            <div class="endpoint-body" id="body-0">

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">⚠️ Violations Found</div>
                    <div class="issues-grid">
                        <div class="issue-item critical">
                            <span class="severity-tag critical">Critical</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Verb in URL path — "get" is redundant and wrong</h4>
                                <p>The word <code>get</code> in <code>/getUsers</code> is completely redundant. The HTTP method <code>GET</code> already communicates the intent. Embedding verbs in URLs is an RPC-style anti-pattern that violates REST's resource-oriented architecture. Every REST-aware tool, proxy, and developer expects URLs to name resources, not actions.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item critical">
                            <span class="severity-tag critical">Critical</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>camelCase URL — violates naming convention</h4>
                                <p><code>getUsers</code> uses camelCase which is not a web URL convention. URLs are case-sensitive on most servers. The standard is lowercase with hyphens for multi-word segments: <code>/users</code> or <code>/user-profiles</code>. camelCase causes inconsistency and potential 404s from case mismatches.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item minor">
                            <span class="severity-tag minor">Minor</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Missing collection semantics — should be plural</h4>
                                <p>Even if the verb were removed, <code>/user</code> (singular) would imply a single resource. A collection endpoint must use the plural form <code>/users</code> to clearly signal it returns a list. Singular paths should be reserved for specific resource instances like <code>/users/5</code>.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">🔄 Before &amp; After</div>
                    <div class="comparison-grid">
                        <div class="code-block broken">
                            <div class="code-block-label">✗ Broken</div>
                            <pre>GET /getUsers</pre>
                        </div>
                        <div class="arrow-cell">→</div>
                        <div class="code-block fixed">
                            <div class="code-block-label">✓ Correct</div>
                            <pre>GET /users</pre>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">📖 REST Principle</div>
                    <div class="principle-box">
                        <h4>🏷️ URLs are nouns — HTTP methods are verbs</h4>
                        <p>A URL is an identifier for a resource. The HTTP method tells the server what to do with it. Combining them is like saying "fetch-the-database" instead of "the database". The correct pattern:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><code>GET /users</code> — retrieve the users collection</li>
                            <li><code>GET /users/5</code> — retrieve user with ID 5</li>
                            <li><code>POST /users</code> — create a new user</li>
                            <li><code>DELETE /users/5</code> — delete user with ID 5</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 2: POST /user/delete/5 -->
        <div class="endpoint-card" data-severities="critical,major" id="card-1">
            <div class="endpoint-header" onclick="toggleCard(1)">
                <span class="method-badge method-post">POST</span>
                <span class="endpoint-path broken">/user/delete/5</span>
                <span class="issue-count-badge">4 issues</span>
                <span class="chevron" id="chevron-1">▼</span>
            </div>
            <div class="endpoint-body" id="body-1">

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">⚠️ Violations Found</div>
                    <div class="issues-grid">
                        <div class="issue-item critical">
                            <span class="severity-tag critical">Critical</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Wrong HTTP method — POST used for deletion</h4>
                                <p><code>POST</code> means "create a new resource" or "submit data for processing." Using it to delete a resource fundamentally breaks the HTTP contract. Deletion must use the <code>DELETE</code> method. This matters because: HTTP caches know <code>DELETE</code> invalidates cached responses, clients know <code>DELETE</code> is idempotent (calling it twice is safe), and security middleware can block <code>DELETE</code> separately from <code>POST</code>.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item critical">
                            <span class="severity-tag critical">Critical</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Verb "delete" embedded in URL path</h4>
                                <p>Same anti-pattern as <code>/getUsers</code>. The word <code>delete</code> in the path is completely redundant when using the <code>DELETE</code> HTTP method. The URL <code>/users/5</code> with method <code>DELETE</code> is unambiguous and correct. Having both is like writing <code>DELETE /delete-users/5</code> — the verb appears twice.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item major">
                            <span class="severity-tag major">Major</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Singular resource name — should be plural</h4>
                                <p><code>/user/delete/5</code> uses the singular <code>user</code>. REST convention requires plural collection names: <code>/users/5</code>. The singular form creates ambiguity — does <code>/user</code> mean the collection or a singleton resource? Plural is unambiguous: <code>/users</code> is the collection, <code>/users/5</code> is one item from it.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item major">
                            <span class="severity-tag major">Major</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Inconsistent naming with other endpoints</h4>
                                <p>This endpoint uses <code>/user/</code> (singular) while <code>/getUsers</code> uses a plural (albeit verb-prefixed) form. Inconsistency means API consumers cannot predict the pattern. If some endpoints are singular and others plural, every endpoint must be individually memorised rather than inferred from convention.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">🔄 Before &amp; After</div>
                    <div class="comparison-grid">
                        <div class="code-block broken">
                            <div class="code-block-label">✗ Broken</div>
                            <pre>POST /user/delete/5</pre>
                        </div>
                        <div class="arrow-cell">→</div>
                        <div class="code-block fixed">
                            <div class="code-block-label">✓ Correct</div>
                            <pre>DELETE /users/5</pre>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">📖 REST Principle</div>
                    <div class="principle-box">
                        <h4>🔧 HTTP methods carry semantic meaning</h4>
                        <p><code>DELETE</code> is idempotent — calling <code>DELETE /users/5</code> once or ten times produces the same result (user 5 is gone). <code>POST</code> is not idempotent — calling it multiple times may create multiple resources. Idempotency is relied upon by:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Retry logic in HTTP clients and load balancers</li>
                            <li>Browser back-button and refresh behaviour</li>
                            <li>CDN and reverse proxy cache invalidation</li>
                            <li>API gateway rate limiting and security policies</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 3: GET /createUser?name=Jo -->
        <div class="endpoint-card" data-severities="critical,major,minor" id="card-2">
            <div class="endpoint-header" onclick="toggleCard(2)">
                <span class="method-badge method-get">GET</span>
                <span class="endpoint-path broken">/createUser?name=Jo</span>
                <span class="issue-count-badge">4 issues</span>
                <span class="chevron" id="chevron-2">▼</span>
            </div>
            <div class="endpoint-body" id="body-2">

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">⚠️ Violations Found</div>
                    <div class="issues-grid">
                        <div class="issue-item critical">
                            <span class="severity-tag critical">Critical</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>GET used to create a resource — catastrophically wrong</h4>
                                <p><code>GET</code> is defined by HTTP as a <strong>safe</strong> method — it must not change server state. Using <code>GET</code> to create a user violates this contract completely. Consequences: browsers prefetch GET URLs (creating phantom users), search engine crawlers index the URL (accidentally creating users), HTTP caches may serve a cached "success" response without hitting the server, and logging/monitoring tools may not flag it as a write operation.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item critical">
                            <span class="severity-tag critical">Critical</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Resource data in query string instead of request body</h4>
                                <p>Query strings (<code>?name=Jo</code>) are for filtering or searching existing resources, not for passing resource creation data. Sending user data in the URL exposes it in: server access logs, browser history, Referer headers sent to third parties, CDN and proxy logs, and analytics tools. This is a <strong>security and privacy violation</strong>. Creation data belongs in the POST request body.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item major">
                            <span class="severity-tag major">Major</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Verb "create" in URL path</h4>
                                <p>The word <code>create</code> in the path is redundant. <code>POST /users</code> already means "create a user in the users collection." The URL should identify the resource collection being posted to, not describe the action. This is the same verb-in-URL anti-pattern as the other endpoints.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item minor">
                            <span class="severity-tag minor">Minor</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>camelCase URL naming</h4>
                                <p><code>createUser</code> uses camelCase. Web URLs should be lowercase. While some servers handle this gracefully, it creates inconsistency and potential case-sensitivity bugs. The correct resource name is simply <code>/users</code> (lowercase, plural, no verb).</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">🔄 Before &amp; After</div>
                    <div class="comparison-grid">
                        <div class="code-block broken">
                            <div class="code-block-label">✗ Broken</div>
                            <pre>GET /createUser?name=Jo</pre>
                        </div>
                        <div class="arrow-cell">→</div>
                        <div class="code-block fixed">
                            <div class="code-block-label">✓ Correct</div>
                            <pre>POST /users
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "name": "Jo"
}</pre>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">📖 REST Principle</div>
                    <div class="principle-box">
                        <h4>📦 Query strings are for filtering — body is for data</h4>
                        <p>The correct use of each part of an HTTP request:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><code>GET /users?role=admin</code> — filter the collection (query string ✓)</li>
                            <li><code>GET /users?page=2&amp;limit=20</code> — paginate (query string ✓)</li>
                            <li><code>POST /users</code> + JSON body — create a user (body ✓)</li>
                            <li><code>PUT /users/5</code> + JSON body — replace user 5 (body ✓)</li>
                            <li><code>GET /users?name=Jo</code> — search by name (query string ✓)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 4: PUT /updateAllUsers -->
        <div class="endpoint-card" data-severities="critical,major" id="card-3">
            <div class="endpoint-header" onclick="toggleCard(3)">
                <span class="method-badge method-put">PUT</span>
                <span class="endpoint-path broken">/updateAllUsers</span>
                <span class="issue-count-badge">3 issues</span>
                <span class="chevron" id="chevron-3">▼</span>
            </div>
            <div class="endpoint-body" id="body-3">

                <div class="section">
                    <div class="section-title">⚠️ Violations Found</div>
                    <div class="issues-grid">
                        <div class="issue-item critical">
                            <span class="severity-tag critical">Critical</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>Verb "update" embedded in URL path</h4>
                                <p>The word <code>update</code> is redundant — the <code>PUT</code> method already communicates the update intent. This is the same verb-in-URL anti-pattern present in every endpoint in this API. The URL should be <code>/users</code> (the collection resource) with <code>PUT</code> or <code>PATCH</code> expressing the update action.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item major">
                            <span class="severity-tag major">Major</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>PUT on entire collection is dangerous and semantically wrong</h4>
                                <p><code>PUT</code> is defined as a <strong>full replacement</strong> of a resource. <code>PUT /users</code> would semantically mean "replace the entire users collection with the request body" — destroying all existing users. This is almost certainly not the intent. If you need to update all users, use <code>PATCH /users</code> with a body describing the partial changes, or reconsider the design (bulk operations often warrant a dedicated sub-resource like <code>POST /users/bulk-update</code>).</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="issue-item major">
                            <span class="severity-tag major">Major</span>
                            <div class="issue-content">
                                <h4>camelCase with embedded verb — naming convention failure</h4>
                                <p><code>updateAllUsers</code> combines three problems: a verb (<code>update</code>), a quantifier (<code>All</code>), and camelCase. REST URLs should be lowercase plural nouns. The "all" qualifier is implicit when targeting a collection endpoint without an ID filter. If partial bulk updates are needed, use query parameters: <code>PATCH /users?role=admin</code>.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
